tAlecky Blythe and “Headphone Verbatim”: a Study of The Girlfriend Experience (2008) -- tIV In Conversation with… -- tFeeling a Responsibility to Art: An Interview with Ella Hickson -- tThe Gordian Knots of Theatre: An Interview with Lucy Kirkwood by Elisabeth Angel-Perez and Aloysia Rousseau -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex of playwrights, theatre practitioners and key concepts0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is a fact that today’s British stages resound with powerfully innovative voices and that, very often, these voices have been those of young women playwrights. This collection of essays gives visibility and pride of place to these fascinating voices by exploring the vitality, inventiveness and particularly strong relevance of these poetics. These women playwrights sometimes invent radically new forms and sometimes experiment with conventional ones in fresh and unexpected ways, as for example when they re-energize naturalism and provide it with new missions. The plays that are addressed are all concerned with the necessity to grasp the complexity of the contemporary world and to further investigate what it means to be human. Intimate or epic, and sometimes both at once, visionary or closer to everyday life, these plays approach the contemporary world through a multitude of prisms – historical, scientific, political and poetic – and open different and visionary perspectives.  aToday’s British stages resound with powerfully innovative voices and, very often, these voices have been those of a new wave of British women playwrights. These women invent radically new forms and experiment with conventional ones in fresh and unexpected ways, as for example when they re-energize naturalism and provide it with new missions. This volume explores the vitality, inventiveness and particularly strong relevance of these new poetics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEnglish dramaxWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Drama.2bisacsh  aContemporary British Drama.  aDramaturgy.  aNew voices.  aWomen Playwrights.1 aAngel-Perez, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngel-Perez, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAngelaki, Vicky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoles, William C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenstreet, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHélie, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, Lianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrudhon, Déborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodríguez, Verónica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Aloysia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRousseau, Aloysia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchaaf, Jeanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStewart, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWatson, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z97831111757820 cEPUBz97831107963770 cprintz978311079622340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311079632240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110796322423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110796322/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  a